# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: angular-displacement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:angular-displacement/absement] In kinematics, **absement** is a measure of sustained displacement of an object from its initial position, i.e. a measure of how far away and for how long.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] The word *absement* is a portmanteau of the words *absence* and *displacement*.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Absement changes as an object remains displaced and stays constant as the object resides at the initial position.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] It is the first time-integral of the displacement (i.e. absement is the area under a displacement vs. time graph), so the displacement is the rate of change (first time-derivative) of the absement.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] The dimension of absement is length multiplied by time.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Its SI unit is **meter second** (m·s), which corresponds to an object having been displaced by 1 meter for 1 second.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] This is not to be confused with a meter per second (m/s), a unit of velocity, the time-derivative of position.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] For example, opening the gate of a gate valve (of rectangular cross section) by 1 mm for 10 seconds yields the same absement of 10 mm·s as opening it by 5 mm for 2 seconds.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] The amount of water having flowed through it is linearly proportional to the absement of the gate, so it is also the same in both cases.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Whenever the rate of change *f*′ of a quantity *f* is proportional to the displacement of an object, the quantity *f* is a linear function of the object's absement.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] For example, when the fuel flow rate is proportional to the position of the throttle lever, then the total amount of fuel consumed is proportional to the lever's absement.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Absement has also been used to model artificial muscles, as well as for real muscle interaction in a physical fitness context.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Absement has also been used to model human posture.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] As the displacement can be seen as a mechanical analogue of electric charge, the absement can be seen as a mechanical analogue of the time-integrated charge, a quantity useful for modelling some types of memory elements.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] In addition to modeling fluid flow and for Lagrangian modeling of electric circuits, absement is used in physical fitness and kinesiology to model muscle bandwidth, and as a new form of physical fitness training.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] In this context, it gives rise to a new quantity called **actergy**, which is to energy as energy is to power.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Actergy has the same units as action (joule-seconds) but is the time-integral of total energy (time-integral of the Hamiltonian rather than time-integral of the Lagrangian).
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Just as displacement and its derivatives form kinematics, so do displacement and its integrals form "integral kinematics".
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Strain absement is the time-integral of strain, and is used extensively in mechanical systems and memsprings.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Absement originally arose in situations involving valves and fluid flow, for which the opening of a valve was by a long, T-shaped handle, which actually varied in angle rather than position.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] The time-integral of angle is called "anglement" and it is approximately equal or proportional to absement for small angles, because the sine of an angle is approximately equal to the angle for small angles.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Building on the concept of anglement, "Einstein's Lane Method" could be used to describe the spatiotemporal trajectory of systems involving rotational motion or angular displacement.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] Einstein’s Lane Method provides a framework for analyzing the curved paths of rotating objects or systems under the influence of gravitational fields, similar to how general relativity describes the bending of spacetime.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] This method would use angular displacements (rather than linear positions) as key variables, integrating them over time, much like the time-integral of angle in anglement.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] In regard to a conjugate variable for absement, the time-integral of momentum, known as momentement, has been proposed.
[src:angular-displacement/absement] This is consistent with Jeltsema's 2012 treatment with charge and flux as the base units rather than current and voltage.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] In mathematics, the **absolute value** or **modulus** of a real number x , denoted $|x|$ , is the (non-negative) magnitude of x measured without regard to its sign.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Namely, $|x|=x$ if x is a positive number, and $|x|=-x$ if x is negative (in which case $-x$ is positive), and $|0|=0$ .
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] For example, the absolute value of 3 is 3, and the absolute value of −3 is also 3.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The absolute value of a number may be thought of as its distance from zero.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Generalisations of the absolute value for real numbers occur in a wide variety of mathematical settings.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] For example, an absolute value is also defined for the complex numbers, the quaternions, ordered rings, fields and vector spaces.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The absolute value is closely related to the notions of magnitude, distance, and norm in various mathematical and physical contexts.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] In 1806, Jean-Robert Argand introduced the term *module*, meaning *unit of measure* in French, specifically for the *complex* absolute value, and it was borrowed into English in 1866 as the Latin equivalent *modulus*.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The term *absolute value* has been used in this sense from at least 1806 in French and 1857 in English.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The notation |x|, with a vertical bar on each side, was introduced by Karl Weierstrass in 1841.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Other names for *absolute value* include *numerical value* and *magnitude*.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The vertical bar notation also appears in a number of other mathematical contexts: for example, when applied to a set, it denotes its cardinality; when applied to a matrix, it denotes its determinant.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Vertical bars denote the absolute value only for algebraic objects for which the notion of an absolute value is defined, notably an element of a normed division algebra, for example, a real number, a complex number, or a quaternion.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] A closely related but distinct notation is the use of vertical bars for either the Euclidean norm or sup norm of a vector in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , although double vertical bars with subscripts ( $\|\cdot \|_{2}$ and $\|\cdot \|_{\infty }$ , respectively) are a more common and less ambiguous notation.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The absolute value of x is thus always either a positive number or zero, but never negative.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] When x itself is negative ( $x<0$ ), then its absolute value is necessarily positive ( $|x|=-x>0$ ).
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] From an analytic geometry point of view, the absolute value of a real number is that number's distance from zero along the real number line, and more generally, the absolute value of the difference of two real numbers (their absolute difference) is the distance between them.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The notion of an abstract distance function in mathematics can be seen to be a generalisation of the absolute value of the difference.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Since the square root symbol represents the unique *positive* square root, when applied to a positive number, it follows that $|x|={\sqrt {x^{2}}}.$ This is equivalent to the definition above, and may be used as an alternative definition of the absolute value of real numbers.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Non-negativity, positive definiteness, and multiplicativity are readily apparent from the definition.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] To see that subadditivity holds, first note that $|a+b|=s(a+b)$ where $s=\pm 1$ , with its sign chosen to make the result positive.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Now, since $-1\cdot x\leq |x|$ and $+1\cdot x\leq |x|$ , it follows that, whichever of $\pm 1$ is the value of s , one has $s\cdot x\leq |x|$ for all real x .
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Some additional useful properties are given below.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] These are either immediate consequences of the definition or implied by the four fundamental properties above.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] These relations may be used to solve inequalities involving absolute values.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The absolute value, as "distance from zero", is used to define the absolute difference between arbitrary real numbers, the standard metric on the real numbers.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Since the complex numbers are not ordered, the definition given at the top for the real absolute value cannot be directly applied to complex numbers.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] However, the geometric interpretation of the absolute value of a real number as its distance from 0 can be generalised.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The absolute value of a complex number is defined by the Euclidean distance of its corresponding point in the complex plane from the origin.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] When the imaginary part y is zero, this coincides with the definition of the absolute value of the real number x .
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The complex absolute value shares the four fundamental properties given above for the real absolute value.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The identity $|z|^{n}=|z^{n}|$ is a special case of multiplicativity that is often useful by itself.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The real absolute value function is continuous everywhere.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] It is differentiable everywhere except for *x* = 0.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] It is monotonically decreasing on the interval (−∞, 0] and monotonically increasing on the interval [0, +∞).
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Since a real number and its opposite have the same absolute value, it is an even function, and is hence not invertible.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The real absolute value function is a piecewise linear, convex function.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] For both real and complex numbers, the absolute value function is idempotent (meaning that the absolute value of any absolute value is itself).
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The absolute value function of a real number returns its value irrespective of its sign, whereas the sign (or signum) function returns a number's sign irrespective of its value.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The formulas can be derived by considering each case $s>t$ and $t>s$ separately.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] From the last formula one can derive also $|t|=\max(t,-t)$ .
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The real absolute value function is an example of a continuous function that achieves a global minimum where the derivative does not exist.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The subdifferential of |x| at *x* = 0 is the interval [−1, 1].
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The complex absolute value function is continuous everywhere but complex differentiable *nowhere* because it violates the Cauchy–Riemann equations.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The second derivative of |x| with respect to x is zero everywhere except zero, where it does not exist.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] As a generalised function, the second derivative may be taken as two times the Dirac delta function.
