[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] supposing the derivative of the sign function is 0.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The absolute value is closely related to the idea of distance.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The above shows that the "absolute value"-distance, for real and complex numbers, agrees with the standard Euclidean distance, which they inherit as a result of considering them as one and two-dimensional Euclidean spaces, respectively.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The definition of absolute value given for real numbers above can be extended to any ordered ring.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The four fundamental properties of the absolute value for real numbers can be used to generalise the notion of absolute value to an arbitrary field, as follows.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Where **0** denotes the additive identity of F.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] It follows from positive-definiteness and multiplicativity that *v*(**1**) = 1, where **1** denotes the multiplicative identity of F.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The real and complex absolute values defined above are examples of absolute values for an arbitrary field.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] An absolute value which satisfies any (hence all) of the above conditions is said to be **non-Archimedean**, otherwise it is said to be Archimedean.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Again the fundamental properties of the absolute value for real numbers can be used, with a slight modification, to generalise the notion to an arbitrary vector space.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The norm of a vector is also called its *length* or *magnitude*.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] When the real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ are considered as the one-dimensional vector space $\mathbb {R} ^{1}$ , the absolute value is a norm, and is the p-norm (see Lp space) for any p.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] In fact the absolute value is the "only" norm on $\mathbb {R} ^{1}$ , in the sense that, for every norm ‖ · ‖ on $\mathbb {R} ^{1}$ , ‖*x*‖ = ‖1‖ ⋅ |*x*|.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The complex absolute value is a special case of the norm in an inner product space, which is identical to the Euclidean norm when the complex plane is identified as the Euclidean plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] Every composition algebra *A* has an involution *x* → *x** called its **conjugation**.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The product in *A* of an element *x* and its conjugate *x** is written *N*(*x*) = *x x** and called the **norm of x**.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ , complex numbers $\mathbb {C}$ , and quaternions $\mathbb {H}$ are all composition algebras with norms given by definite quadratic forms.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] The absolute value in these division algebras is given by the square root of the composition algebra norm.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] In general, the norm of a composition algebra may be a quadratic form that is not definite and has null vectors.
[src:angular-displacement/absolute-value] However, as in the case of division algebras, when an element *x* has a non-zero norm, then *x* has a multiplicative inverse given by *x**/*N*(*x*).
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] In physics, **acceleration** is a measure of how fast and in what direction an object's speed and direction of motion are changing.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] It is defined as the rate of change of the velocity.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Like velocity, acceleration has a magnitude and a direction, making it a vector quantity.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The SI unit for acceleration is metre per second squared (m⋅s−2, m/s2).
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The **tangential acceleration** of an object is the component of the **acceleration** which is in the same direction as the motion (or tangential velocity) of the object.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] When the velocity of the object does not change direction, this is called **linear acceleration**.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] **Deceleration** or **retardation**, on the other hand, is the component of the acceleration in the opposite (or antiparallel) direction to the tangential velocity.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] **Radial acceleration** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motions) is the component of the acceleration that changes the direction of the object's velocity.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] In Newtonian mechanics, the acceleration of a mass arises from forces acting on it, with its *net* acceleration being a result of the *net* force acting on it.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] By Newton's second law, the magnitude of the *net* acceleration will be proportional to the magnitude of the *net* force acting on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object, while the direction of the *net* acceleration will be the same as the direction of the *net* force.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] An object's average acceleration ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}$ over a period of time is its change in velocity, $\Delta \mathbf {v}$ , divided by the duration of the period, $\Delta t$ .
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Mathematically, ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}={\frac {\Delta \mathbf {v} }{\Delta t}}.$ The average acceleration is the simplest way to measure acceleration, requiring only knowledge of the change in velocity and the change in time.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] In a strict sense, the average acceleration is the only *true* acceleration one is able to directly measure without appealing to an empirical law, meaning that it is the most fundamental form of acceleration measurement.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The average acceleration is most often used to approximate the kinematics of an object by assuming that the velocity changes linearly with time.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Instantaneous acceleration is the limit of the average acceleration over an infinitesimal interval of time.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Acceleration has the dimensions of velocity (L/T) divided by time, i.e.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The SI unit of acceleration is the metre per second squared (m s−2); or "metre per second per second", as the velocity in metres per second changes by the acceleration value, every second.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] An object moving in a circular motion—such as a satellite orbiting the Earth—is accelerating due to the change of direction of motion, although its speed may be constant.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] In this case it is said to be undergoing *centripetal* (directed towards the center) acceleration.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Proper acceleration, the acceleration of a body relative to a free-fall condition, is measured by an instrument called an accelerometer.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Newton's second law is normally applied in an inertial reference frame.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] In a reference frame accelerating with acceleration a (in one dimension), Newton's laws can still be used by introducing an inertial force (fictitious force) $F=-ma$ on a mass m , opposite the acceleration of the frame.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] This accounts for the tendency of the mass to maintain its inertial motion—to stay "as is," at rest or moving at constant velocity—while the frame accelerates.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] One example is that a person in an elevator feels heavier or lighter as the elevator accelerates or decelerates.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] If m is known, measurement of the supporting force on the mass can be used to infer the acceleration; this is the principle of a mechanical accelerometer.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] In general relativity, gravity and inertial acceleration may be locally indistinguishable (see General relativity).
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] As speeds approach the speed of light, relativistic effects become increasingly large.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] When a vehicle starts from a standstill (zero velocity, in an inertial frame of reference) and travels in a straight line at increasing speeds, it is accelerating in the direction of travel.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] If the vehicle turns, an acceleration occurs toward the new direction and changes its motion vector.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The component of acceleration of the vehicle in the direction of its velocity is called a **linear acceleration** or **tangential acceleration**, its effect being the passengers on board experience as a fictitious force pushing them back into or away from their seats.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] When changing direction, the component of the acceleration perpendicular to the velocity is called **radial** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motion), the reaction to which the passengers experience as a centrifugal force (another fictitious force).
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] If the speed of the vehicle decreases, this is an acceleration in the opposite direction of the velocity vector, sometimes called **deceleration** or **retardation**, and passengers experience the reaction to deceleration as an inertial force pushing them forward.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Such deceleration is often achieved by retrorocket burning in spacecraft.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Both acceleration and deceleration are treated the same, as they are both changes in velocity.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Each of these accelerations (tangential, radial, deceleration) is felt by passengers until their relative (differential) velocity is neutralised in reference to the acceleration due to change in speed.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] where **u**n is the unit (inward) normal vector to the particle's trajectory (also called *the principal normal*), and **r** is its instantaneous radius of curvature based upon the osculating circle at time t.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Geometrical analysis of three-dimensional space curves, which explains tangent, (principal) normal and binormal, is described by the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] A frequently cited example of uniform acceleration is that of an object in free fall in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The acceleration of a falling body in the absence of resistances to motion is dependent only on the gravitational field strength g (also called *acceleration due to gravity*).
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] In particular, the motion can be resolved into two orthogonal parts, one of constant velocity and the other according to the above equations.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] As Galileo showed, the net result is parabolic motion, which describes, e.g., the trajectory of a projectile in vacuum near the surface of Earth.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] plane in a point of an arbitrary curve in any higher dimension.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] In uniform circular motion, that is moving with constant *speed* along a circular path, a particle experiences an acceleration resulting from the change of the direction of the velocity vector, while its magnitude remains constant.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The derivative of the location of a point on a curve with respect to time, i.e. its velocity, turns out to be always exactly tangential to the curve, respectively orthogonal to the radius in this point.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Since in uniform motion the velocity in the tangential direction does not change, the acceleration must be in radial direction, pointing to the center of the circle.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] This acceleration constantly changes the direction of the velocity to be tangent in the neighbouring point, thereby rotating the velocity vector along the circle.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] This acceleration and the mass of the particle determine the necessary centripetal force, directed *toward* the centre of the circle, as the net force acting on this particle to keep it in this uniform circular motion.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The so-called 'centrifugal force', appearing to act outward on the body, is a so-called pseudo force experienced in the frame of reference of the body in circular motion, due to the body's linear momentum, a vector tangent to the circle of motion.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The tangential component is given by the angular acceleration $\alpha$ , i.e., the rate of change $\alpha ={\dot {\omega }}$ of the angular speed $\omega$ times the radius r .
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The sign of the tangential component of the acceleration is determined by the sign of the angular acceleration ( $\alpha$ ), and the tangent is always directed at right angles to the radius vector.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] In multi-dimensional Cartesian coordinate systems, acceleration is broken up into components that correspond with each dimensional axis of the coordinate system.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] The special theory of relativity describes the behaviour of objects travelling relative to other objects at speeds approaching that of light in vacuum.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Newtonian mechanics is exactly revealed to be an approximation to reality, valid to great accuracy at lower speeds.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] As the relevant speeds increase toward the speed of light, acceleration no longer follows classical equations.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] As speeds approach that of light, the acceleration produced by a given force decreases, becoming infinitesimally small as light speed is approached; an object with mass can approach this speed asymptotically, but never reach it.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Unless the state of motion of an object is known, it is impossible to distinguish whether an observed force is due to gravity or to acceleration—gravity and inertial acceleration have identical effects.
[src:angular-displacement/acceleration] Albert Einstein called this the equivalence principle, and said that only observers who feel no force at all—including the force of gravity—are justified in concluding that they are not accelerating.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] In physics, **action** is a scalar quantity that describes how the balance of kinetic versus potential energy of a physical system changes with trajectory.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Action is significant because it is an input to the principle of stationary action, an approach to classical mechanics that is simpler for multiple objects.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Action and the variational principle are used in Feynman's formulation of quantum mechanics and in general relativity.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] For systems with small values of action close to the Planck constant, quantum effects are significant.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] More formally, action is a mathematical functional which takes the trajectory (also called path or history) of the system as its argument and has a real number as its result.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Generally, the action takes different values for different paths.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Action has dimensions of energy × time or momentum × length, and its SI unit is joule-second (like the Planck constant h).
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Introductory physics often begins with Newton's laws of motion, relating force and motion; action is part of a completely equivalent alternative approach with practical and educational advantages.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] However, the concept took many decades to supplant Newtonian approaches and remains a challenge to introduce to students.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The kinetic energy of a ball of mass m is ⁠1/2⁠*mv*2 where v is the velocity of the ball; the potential energy is mgx where g is the acceleration due to gravity and x its height.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] This makes the action an input to the powerful stationary-action principle for classical and for quantum mechanics.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Newton's equations of motion for the ball can be derived from the action using the stationary-action principle, but the advantages of action-based mechanics only begin to appear in cases where Newton's laws are difficult to apply.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Replace the ball with an electron: classical mechanics fails but stationary action continues to work.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The energy difference in the simple action definition, kinetic minus potential energy, is generalized and called the Lagrangian for more complex cases.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The Planck constant, written as h, is the quantum (the minimal possible amount) of action.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] It is related to the quantum of angular momentum, ħ, by the relation *ħ* = ⁠*h*/2*π*⁠.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] These constants have units of energy times time.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] They appear in all significant quantum equations, such as the uncertainty principle and the de Broglie wavelength.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Whenever the value of the action approaches the Planck constant, quantum effects are significant.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Pierre Louis Maupertuis and Leonhard Euler working in the 1740s developed early versions of the action principle.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Joseph Louis Lagrange clarified the mathematics when he invented the calculus of variations.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] William Rowan Hamilton made the next big breakthrough, formulating Hamilton's principle in 1853.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Hamilton's principle became the cornerstone for classical work with different forms of action until Richard Feynman and Julian Schwinger developed quantum action principles.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Expressed in mathematical language, using the calculus of variations, the evolution of a physical system (that is, how the system actually progresses from one state to another) corresponds to a stationary point (usually, a minimum) of the action.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Action has the dimensions of [energy] × [time], and its SI unit is joule-second, which is identical to the unit of angular momentum.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Several different definitions of "the action" are in common use in physics.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The action is usually an integral over time.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] However, when the action pertains to fields, it may be integrated over spatial variables as well.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] In some cases, the action is integrated along the path followed by the physical system.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The action is typically represented as an integral over time, taken along the path of the system between the initial time and the final time of the development of the system: ${\mathcal {S}}=\int _{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}L\,dt,$ where the integrand L is called the Lagrangian.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] For the action integral to be well-defined, the trajectory has to be bounded in time and space.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Most commonly, the term is used for a functional 𝒮 which takes a function of time and (for fields) space as input and returns a scalar.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] In classical mechanics, the input function is the evolution **q**(*t*) of the system between times *t*1 and *t*2, where **q** represents the generalized coordinates.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] According to Hamilton's principle, the true evolution **q**true(*t*) is an evolution for which the action 𝒮[**q**(*t*)] is stationary (a minimum, maximum, or a saddle point).
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] This principle results in the equations of motion in Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] In addition to the action functional, there is another functional called the *abbreviated action*.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] In the abbreviated action, the input function is the *path* followed by the physical system without regard to its parameterization by time.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] For example, the path of a planetary orbit is an ellipse, and the path of a particle in a uniform gravitational field is a parabola; in both cases, the path does not depend on how fast the particle traverses the path.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] According to Maupertuis's principle, the true path of the system is a path for which the abbreviated action is stationary.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] When the total energy E is conserved, the Hamilton–Jacobi equation can be solved with the additive separation of variables: $S(q_{1},\dots ,q_{N},t)=W(q_{1},\dots ,q_{N})-E\cdot t,$ where the time-independent function *W*(*q*1,*q*2,…,*qN*) is called *Hamilton's characteristic function*.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The corresponding canonical variable conjugate to *Jk* is its "angle" *wk*, for reasons described more fully under action-angle coordinates.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The integration is only over a single variable *qk* and, therefore, unlike the integrated dot product in the abbreviated action integral above.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The *Jk* variable equals the change in *Sk*(*qk*) as *qk* is varied around the closed path.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] For several physical systems of interest, *Jk* is either a constant or varies very slowly; hence, the variable *Jk* is often used in perturbation calculations and in determining adiabatic invariants.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] For example, they are used in the calculation of planetary and satellite orbits.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Physical laws are frequently expressed as differential equations, which describe how physical quantities such as position and momentum change continuously with time, space or a generalization thereof.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Given the initial and boundary conditions for the situation, the "solution" to these empirical equations is one or more functions that describe the behavior of the system and are called *equations of motion*.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The action principle provides deep insights into physics, and is an important concept in modern theoretical physics.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Various action principles and related concepts are summarized below.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] In classical mechanics, Maupertuis's principle (named after Pierre Louis Maupertuis) states that the path followed by a physical system is the one of least length (with a suitable interpretation of path and length).
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Maupertuis's principle uses the abbreviated action between two generalized points on a path.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Hamilton's principle states that the differential equations of motion for *any* physical system can be re-formulated as an equivalent integral equation.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Thus, there are two distinct approaches for formulating dynamical models.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Hamilton's principle applies not only to the classical mechanics of a single particle, but also to classical fields such as the electromagnetic and gravitational fields.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Hamilton's principal function *S* = *S*(*q*,*t*;*q*0,*t*0) is obtained from the action functional 𝒮 by fixing the initial time *t*0 and the initial endpoint *q*0, while allowing the upper time limit t and the second endpoint q to vary.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The Hamilton's principal function satisfies the Hamilton–Jacobi equation, a formulation of classical mechanics.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Due to a similarity with the Schrödinger equation, the Hamilton–Jacobi equation provides, arguably, the most direct link with quantum mechanics.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] In Lagrangian mechanics, the requirement that the action integral be stationary under small perturbations is equivalent to a set of differential equations (called the Euler–Lagrange equations) that may be obtained using the calculus of variations.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The **action principle** can be extended to obtain the equations of motion for fields, such as the electromagnetic field or gravitational field.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Maxwell's equations can be derived as conditions of stationary action.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The Einstein equation utilizes the *Einstein–Hilbert action* as constrained by a variational principle.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The trajectory (path in spacetime) of a body in a gravitational field can be found using the action principle.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] For a free falling body, this trajectory is a geodesic.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Implications of symmetries in a physical situation can be found with the action principle, together with the Euler–Lagrange equations, which are derived from the action principle.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] An example is Noether's theorem, which states that to every continuous symmetry in a physical situation there corresponds a conservation law (and conversely).
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] This deep connection requires that the action principle be assumed.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] In quantum mechanics, the system does not follow a single path whose action is stationary, but the behavior of the system depends on all permitted paths and the value of their action.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The action corresponding to the various paths is used to calculate the path integral, which gives the probability amplitudes of the various outcomes.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Although equivalent in classical mechanics with Newton's laws, the **action principle** is better suited for generalizations and plays an important role in modern physics.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] Indeed, this principle is one of the great generalizations in physical science.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] It is best understood within quantum mechanics, particularly in Richard Feynman's path integral formulation, where it arises out of destructive interference of quantum amplitudes.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The action principle can be generalized still further.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] For example, the action need not be an integral, because nonlocal actions are possible.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] The configuration space need not even be a functional space, given certain features such as noncommutative geometry.
[src:angular-displacement/action-physics] However, a physical basis for these mathematical extensions remains to be established experimentally.
[src:angular-displacement/addison-wesley] The Addison–Wesley Professional Imprint produces content including books, eBooks, and video for the professional IT worker including developers, programmers, managers, system administrators.
[src:angular-displacement/addison-wesley] Classic titles include *The Art of Computer Programming*, *The C++ Programming Language*, *The Mythical Man-Month*, and *Design Patterns*.
[src:angular-displacement/addison-wesley] Lew Addison Cummings and Melbourne Wesley Cummings founded Addison–Wesley in 1942, with the first book published by Addison–Wesley being Massachusetts Institute of Technology professor Francis Weston Sears' *Mechanics*.
[src:angular-displacement/addison-wesley] Its first computer book was *Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, by Wilkes, Wheeler, and Gill.
[src:angular-displacement/addison-wesley] Benjamin Company, and merged it with the Cummings division of the company to form Benjamin Cummings.
[src:angular-displacement/addison-wesley] It was purchased by the global publishing and education company Pearson PLC in 1988 and became part of Addison Wesley Longman in 1994.
[src:angular-displacement/addison-wesley] The trade publishing division of Addison–Wesley was sold to Perseus Books Group in 1997, leaving Addison–Wesley as solely an educational publisher.
[src:angular-displacement/addison-wesley] Pearson acquired the educational division of Simon & Schuster in 1998, and merged it with Addison Wesley Longman to form Pearson Education and subsequently rebranded to Pearson in 2011.
[src:angular-displacement/addison-wesley] Pearson moved the former Addison Wesley Longman offices from Reading, Massachusetts, to Boston in 2004.
[src:angular-displacement/addison-wesley] Its current executives hail from the original Addison–Wesley with a storied history of their own.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut was born in Paris, France, to Jean-Baptiste and Catherine Petit Clairaut.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] The couple had 20 children, however only a few of them survived childbirth.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] He mastered Euclidean geometry and algebra by nine.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] At ten he studied conic sections and the calculus using *Analyse des Infiniment Petits* (1696) by Guillaume de l'Hôpital.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] At the age of twelve he wrote a memoir on four geometrical curves and under his father's tutelage he made such rapid progress in the subject that in his thirteenth year he read before the Académie française an account of the properties of four curves which he had discovered.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] When only sixteen he finished a treatise on Tortuous Curves, *Recherches sur les courbes a double courbure*, which, on its publication in 1731, procured his admission into the Royal Academy of Sciences, although he was below the legal age as he was only eighteen.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] He gave a path-breaking formulae called the distance formulae which helps to find out the distance between any 2 points on the cartesian or XY plane.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut never married and known for leading an active social life.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society of London on 27 October 1737.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] In his research on the calculus, Clairaut discovered the equality of mixed partial derivatives (Clairaut's theorem).
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] He gave a condition under which the differential equation $M(x,y)\,dx+N(x,y)\,dy=0$ was exact, namely, $M_{y}=N_{x}$ .
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] He showed that a differential equation of the form $y=xy'+f(y')$ , now known as Clairaut's equation, could by solved by substituting $p=y'$ and differentiating both sides.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] He also established the existence of the integrating factor for first-order linear differential equations.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] However, he had been anticipated by Nicolas Fatio de Dullier in 1687, and by Johann Bernoulli in a lesson given to L’Hôpital.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] In 1741, Clairaut published *Éléments de Géométrie*, aimed at beginners.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] For Clairaut, it was imperative for students to make discoveries themselves in a form of active, experiential learning.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] He began by comparing geometric shapes to measurements of land, a familiar topic, and covered lines, shapes, and even some three dimensional objects.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Throughout the book, he copiously related geometry to other branches of mathematics as well as physics and astronomy.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Some of the theories and learning methods outlined in the book are still used by teachers today, in geometry and other topics.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] This textbook was so popular that it went through six editions.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] In the eighteenth century, Carl Friedrich Gauss extended the contributions of Clairaut and Christiaan Huygens in the geometry introducing the notion of Gaussian curvature.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut's *Éléments de Algèbre* (1740) was also well-received in Continental Europe.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Its sixth edition was published in 1801.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] In 1736, together with Pierre Louis Maupertuis, he took part in the expedition to Lapland, which was undertaken for the purpose of estimating a degree of the meridian arc.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] The goal of the excursion was to determine the figure of the Earth and to test whether the Earth was an oblate spheroid, as Sir Isaac Newton had claimed in his book *Principia*, or that it was an oblong, as Giovanni Cassini had thought.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Before the expedition team returned to Paris, Clairaut sent his calculations to the Royal Society of London.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] The writing was later published by the society in the 1736–37 volume of *Philosophical Transactions.* Initially, Clairaut disagreed with Newton's conclusion.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] In the article, he outlines several key problems that effectively disprove Newton's calculations, and provides some solutions to the complications.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] The issues addressed include calculating gravitational attraction, the rotation of an ellipsoid on its axis, and the difference in density of an ellipsoid on its axes.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] This meant not only that the Earth is an ellipsoid, but it is flattened more at the poles and is wider at the center, that is, an oblate spheroid.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] His article in *Philosophical Transactions* created much controversy, as he addressed the problems of Newton's theory, but provided few solutions to how to fix the calculations.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] After his return, he published his treatise *Théorie de la figure de la terre* (1743).
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] In this work he promulgated a result, now known as Clairaut's theorem, which connects the gravity at points on the surface of a rotating ellipsoid with the compression and the centrifugal force at the equator.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] His formula gave the Earth's gravitational field strength as a function of latitude.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Under the assumption that the Earth was composed of concentric ellipsoidal shells of uniform density, Clairaut's theorem could be applied to it, and allowed the eccentricity (or deviation from being a perfect sphere) of the Earth to be calculated from surface measurements of gravity.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] In 1849 George Stokes showed that Clairaut's result was true whatever the interior constitution or density of the Earth, provided the surface was a spheroid of equilibrium of small eccentricity.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] One of the most controversial issues of the 18th century was the problem of three bodies, or how the Earth, Moon, and Sun are attracted to one another.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] With the use of the recently founded Leibnizian calculus, Clairaut was able to solve the problem using four differential equations.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] He was also able to incorporate Newton's inverse-square law and law of attraction into his solution, with minor edits to it.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] However, these equations only offered approximate measurement, and no exact calculations.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Another issue still remained with the three body problem; how the Moon rotates on its apsides.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Even Newton could account for only half of the motion of the apsides.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] In fact, Clairaut had at first deemed the dilemma so inexplicable, that he was on the point of publishing a new hypothesis as to the law of attraction.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] The question of the apsides was a heated debate topic in Europe.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Along with Clairaut, there were two other mathematicians who were racing to provide the first explanation for the three body problem; Leonhard Euler and Jean le Rond d'Alembert.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Euler and d'Alembert were arguing against the use of Newtonian laws to solve the three-body problem.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Euler in particular believed that the inverse square law needed revision to accurately calculate the apsides of the Moon.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Despite the hectic competition to come up with the correct solution, Clairaut obtained an ingenious approximate solution of the problem of the three bodies.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] In 1750 he gained the prize of the St Petersburg Academy for his essay *Théorie de la lune*; the team made up of Clairaut, Jérome Lalande and Nicole Reine Lepaute successfully computed the date of the 1759 return of Halley's comet.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] The *Théorie de la lune* is strictly Newtonian in character.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] This contains the explanation of the motion of the apsis.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] It occurred to him to carry the approximation to the third order, and he thereupon found that the result was in accordance with the observations.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] This was followed in 1754 by some lunar tables, which he computed using a form of the discrete Fourier transform.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] The newfound solution to the problem of three bodies ended up meaning more than proving Newton's laws correct.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] The unravelling of the problem of three bodies also had practical importance.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] It allowed sailors to determine the longitudinal direction of their ships, which was crucial not only in sailing to a location, but finding their way home as well.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] This held economic implications as well, because sailors were able to more easily find destinations of trade based on the longitudinal measures.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] In the same work, Clairaut introduced for the first time the theory of potentials, known by that name since the 1828 essay of George Green.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut subsequently wrote various papers on the orbit of the Moon, and on the motion of comets as affected by the perturbation of the planets, particularly on the path of Halley's comet.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] He also used applied mathematics to study Venus, taking accurate measurements of the planet's size and distance from the Earth.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] This was the first precise reckoning of the planet's size.
[src:angular-displacement/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut used his own contributions to celestial mechanics and astronomy to assist Émilie du Châtelet in her translation and commentary of Newton's *Principia*.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The **American Mathematical Society** (**AMS**) is an association of professional mathematicians dedicated to the interests of mathematical research and scholarship, and serves the national and international community through its publications, meetings, advocacy and other programs.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The society is one of the four parts of the Joint Policy Board for Mathematics and a member of the Conference Board of the Mathematical Sciences.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS was founded in 1888 as the **New York Mathematical Society**, the brainchild of Thomas Fiske, who was impressed by the London Mathematical Society on a visit to England.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] John Howard Van Amringe became the first president while Fiske became secretary.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The society soon decided to publish a journal, but ran into some resistance over concerns about competing with the *American Journal of Mathematics*.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The result was the *Bulletin of the American Mathematical Society*, with Fiske as editor-in-chief.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The de facto journal, as intended, was influential in increasing membership.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The popularity of the *Bulletin* soon led to the launches of the *Transactions of the American Mathematical Society* and *Proceedings of the American Mathematical Society*, which were also de facto journals.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] In 1891, Charlotte Scott of Britain became the first woman to join the AMS, then called the New York Mathematical Society.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The society reorganized under its present name (American Mathematical Society) and became a national society in 1894, and that year Scott became the first woman on the first Council of the society.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] In 1927 Anna Pell-Wheeler became the first woman to present a lecture at the society's Colloquium.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] In 1951 there was a southeastern sectional meeting of the Mathematical Association of America in Nashville.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] Holloway came to the meeting and were able to attend the scientific sessions.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] However, the organizer for the closing banquet refused to honor the reservations of these four mathematicians.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] (Letters in Science, August 10, 1951, pp.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] Bylaws were not changed, but non-discriminatory policies were established and have been strictly observed since then.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] Also in 1951, the American Mathematical Society's headquarters moved from New York City to Providence, Rhode Island.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The society later added an office in Ann Arbor, Michigan in 1965 and an office in Washington, D.C. in 1992.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] In 1954 the society called for the creation of a new teaching degree, a Doctor of Arts in Mathematics, similar to a PhD but without a research thesis.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] In the 1970s, as reported in "A Brief History of the Association for Women in Mathematics: The Presidents' Perspectives" by Lenore Blum, "In those years the AMS was governed by what could only be called an 'old boys network,' closed to all but those in the inner circle." Mary W.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] Gray challenged that situation by "sitting in on the Council meeting in Atlantic City.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] When she was told she had to leave, she refused saying she would wait until the police came.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] (Mary relates the story somewhat differently: When she was told she had to leave, she responded she could find no rules in the by-laws restricting attendance at Council meetings.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] Julia Robinson was the first female president of the American Mathematical Society (1983–1984), but was unable to complete her term as she was suffering from leukemia.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] In 1988, the *Journal of the American Mathematical Society* was created, as the flagship journal of the AMS.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The American Mathematical Society plays a significant role in advancing mathematical research by fostering collaboration, supporting early-career researchers, and maintaining influential publications and databases.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS facilitates collaboration among mathematicians through a variety of programs aimed at different career stages.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The Mathematical Research Communities, established in 2008, provides early-career researchers with opportunities to engage in intensive research workshops, collaborate with peers, and receive mentoring from senior mathematicians.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] These programs often lead to the formation of long-term research groups that contribute to emerging fields in mathematics.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] In addition, the AMS supports Research Experiences for Undergraduates through advocacy and funding partnerships, ensuring that undergraduate students are exposed to high-level mathematical research.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS also offers travel grants and fellowships to encourage participation in international conferences and collaborative research projects.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] Chelsea Publishing Company was acquired in 1997 and continues to publish a portion of the company's original catalog under **AMS Chelsea Publishing**.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] AMS Chelsea Publishing also publishes new titles.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS advocates for federal funding for mathematical research.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] It collaborates with organizations such as the National Science Foundation and the National Academy of Sciences to promote funding initiatives.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS is also a member of the Joint Policy Board for Mathematics, which works with policymakers to emphasize the role of mathematics in technological advancements and national security.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] In partnership with the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the AMS has contributed to discussions on STEM workforce development and the applications of mathematics in areas such as cybersecurity and data science.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The society has supported initiatives for stable funding in mathematical research, citing its importance in economic growth and scientific development.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS, along with more than a dozen other organizations, holds the largest annual research mathematics meeting in the world, the Joint Mathematics Meeting, in early January.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The 2019 Joint Mathematics Meeting in Baltimore drew approximately 6,000 attendees.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] Each of the four regional sections of the AMS (Central, Eastern, Southeastern, and Western) holds meetings in the spring and fall of each year.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The society also co-sponsors meetings with other international mathematical societies.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS selects an annual class of Fellows who have made outstanding contributions to the advancement of mathematics.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS publishes *Mathematical Reviews*, a database of reviews of mathematical publications, various journals, and books, and maintains the associated online version *MathSciNet*.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] In 1997 the AMS acquired Chelsea Publishing Company, which it uses as an imprint.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] In 2017, the AMS acquired MAA Press, the book publishing program of the Mathematical Association of America.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS has continued to publish books under the MAA Press imprint.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] Some prizes are awarded jointly with other mathematical organizations.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS is led by the president, who is elected for a two-year term, and cannot serve for two consecutive terms.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The current president is Ravi Vakil, who took office in February 2025.
[src:angular-displacement/american-mathematical-society] The AMS has an executive director who sits at the helm of the organization, steering it, managing its operations, and carrying out its mission according to the strategic direction of the board of trustees.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Angular displacement may be signed, indicating the direction of rotation (e.g., clockwise versus counterclockwise); it may also be greater (in absolute value) than a full turn if the rotation was.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] When a body with orientation rotates about an axis, the motion of the orientation must be taken into account, such as how the yaw, pitch and roll of a plane all result in different, new orientations.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Each part of the object experiences circular motion as it undergoes the rotation.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] The simplest case is that of the rigid body in which the object itself does not change.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Precisely, this is when the distances between all the particles remain constant throughout the body's motion, as opposed to it having internally moving parts parts or accumulating or releasing parts of itself.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Many real bodies are approximated as rigid bodies, such as airplanes in flight simulations.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] In the example illustrated to the left (or above in some mobile versions), a particle or body P is at a fixed distance *r* from the origin, *O*, rotating counterclockwise.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] It becomes important to then represent the position of particle P in terms of its polar coordinates (*r*, *θ*).
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] In this particular example, the value of *θ* is changing, while the value of the radius remains the same.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Angular displacement may be expressed with the unit radian or degree.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] For example, if a body rotates 360° around a circle of radius *r*, the angular displacement is given by the distance traveled around the circumference - which is 2π*r* - divided by the radius: $\theta ={\frac {2\pi r}{r}}$ which easily simplifies to: $\theta =2\pi$ .
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Therefore, 1 revolution is $2\pi$ radians.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] The above definition is part of the International System of Quantities (ISQ), formalized in the international standard ISO 80000-3 (Space and time), and adopted in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Angular displacement may be signed, indicating the sense of rotation (e.g., clockwise); it may also be greater (in absolute value) than a full turn.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] In the ISQ/SI, angular displacement is used to define the *number of revolutions*, *N* = θ/(2π rad), a ratio and hence a quantity of dimension one.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] In three dimensions, angular displacement is an entity with a direction and a magnitude.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] The direction specifies the axis of rotation, which always exists by virtue of the Euler's rotation theorem; the magnitude specifies the rotation in radians about that axis (using the right-hand rule to determine direction).
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Despite having direction and magnitude, angular displacement is not a vector because it does not obey the commutative law for addition.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Nevertheless, when dealing with infinitesimal rotations, second order infinitesimals can be discarded and in this case commutativity appears.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Several ways to describe rotations exist, like rotation matrices or Euler angles.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Given that any frame in the space can be described by a rotation matrix, the displacement among them can also be described by a rotation matrix.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] Being $A_{0}$ and $A_{f}$ two matrices, the angular displacement matrix between them can be obtained as ⁠ $\Delta A=A_{f}A_{0}^{-1}$ ⁠.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] When this product is performed having a very small difference between both frames we will obtain a matrix close to the identity.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] In the limit, we will have an infinitesimal rotation matrix.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] An infinitesimal rotation matrix or differential rotation matrix is a matrix representing an infinitely small rotation.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] where I is the identity matrix, $d\theta$ is vanishingly small, and ⁠ $A\in {\mathfrak {so}}(n)$ ⁠.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] The computation rules for infinitesimal rotation matrices are the usual ones except that infinitesimals of second order are dropped.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] With these rules, these matrices do not satisfy all the same properties as ordinary finite rotation matrices under the usual treatment of infinitesimals.
[src:angular-displacement/angular-displacement] It turns out that *the order in which infinitesimal rotations are applied is irrelevant*.
